ense. After this nuanced exploration of an Anlo-Ewe theory of inner states and their way of delineating external experience, readers will never again take for granted the "naturalness" of sight, touch, taste, hearing, and smell.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAnlo (African people)xPsychology. 0aAnlo (African people)xSocialization. 0aAnlo African peoplexPsychology. 0aAnlo African peoplexSocialization. 0aSenses and sensationvCross-cultural studies. 0aSenses and sensationxCross-cultural studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aafrica.  aafrican community.  aanlo culture.  aanlo ewe.  aanlo society.  aanthropologists.  abalance.  acultural anthropology.  acultural knowledge.  acultural meaning.  acultural perspective.  acultural traditions.  ademographic studies.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  aghana.  ahearing.  ainnate senses.  ainner states.  ametaphorical senses.  anonfiction.  aperception.  aphilosophy.  aphysical senses.  asensorium.  asensory perception.  asight.  asmell.  asocial cultural.  asocial science.  ataste.  atouch.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093654640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936546423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520936546/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles